Let´s talk about some possibly better knews than expected here. No question, that this will end above 200K, and no question that many experts are talking about billions of infected people in the next year/s with millions dying and shutdowns happening everywhere. But I see one thing, that gives me hope (of course also hoping, that the reason isn´t just the lack of testing kits and also fearing bad briers on all the other questions related to corona, I´m in): daily growth rates are not increasing further in the regions I analysed (with my homecountry germany the only bigger exception in Europe (where this is currently growing fastest)). China, South Korea, Japan, Hong Kong, Singapore have all been relatively stable for a while now. Growth in most countries in Europe isn´t as bad as it was in the last days. Although we have got 162 of about 200 countries in the world on the list now, it looks like even the numbers of the worst growing countries on worldometers could stop growing at 20%+ per day with growth even declining in many places. There are some worries, just looking at todays numbers: Malaysia, Pakistan, parts of South Amerika have huge growth rates today, and there as well as in Africa the medical situation might not be perfect. But the overall picture looks better today. I wish, it was true and @ddorsey , as we were on the same pessimistic track for a while so far, would see it the same way (being right with optimistic views feels better than with pessimistic  ones !). In spite of the expert´s theories about 50-80% worldwide infection rates - now I really hope, that the chimp will win this. The worldometers data at least is getting better for it ;-)
I´d prefer positive responses to my little optimism (after having felt quite beat down from the UK governments analysis (my father is 76, and it really sounded like "all above 70 are in greatest danger" to me) yesterday) from you as well:
@Prognosticating-Beek @Dillyweed @ManuPV @Greyowlsova @dlaiocean @Anneinak

We just blew past 100K cases. Meanwhile I am hoping that these infections might follow the same seasonal course as the common cold class of coronaviruses and transmission fall to almost zero by April or May. If not -- urk. I'm in a high risk category if I catch it, but low risk in that my husband and I work from home on 20 acres in a rural area, and are prepared to isolate ourselves.
