Updated to reflect 3 developments:
1.  Chinese National Health Commission changing the definition of "Confirmed cases" - patients who tested positive for the virus but showed no symptoms will no longer be included in the count - this will significantly reduce the case count increases artificially; 
2.  Xi's comments that the measures taken so far is too drastic and adversely impacting the economy.  This essentially sends the signal that numbers need to come down so the economic engine can be restarted;
3.  The impact of the above is almost immediate:  the number of new cases, which has been on a running average of 3,200 daily for the past week, drops to below 2,000 this morning (https://ncov.dxy.cn/); The question is not about the actual number of cases - which may now never be known.  Rather, the question is about WHO numbers.  WHO will take the side of China whatever it is.  Hence will need to amend forecast.

Updating my forecast for 3 reasons:
(1) slowing down of increase of cases - the days to double slowed from initial 2 days to 6 days this morning, according to statistics from https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports/ and https://ncov.dxy.cn/;
(2) reported under-reporting by Chinese authorities, partly due to lack of test kits, e.g. death of Japanese in Wuhan;
(3) the tendency of WHO chief to agree with whatever the Chinese is doing:  https://www.ft.com/content/57c6a1d6-49a7-11ea-aeb3-955839e06441
As Chinese authorities and WHO are essentially the ones that keep the scores, the ultimate scores will be what they will it, within probabilitistic range.
